article.description:
Michael Olowokandi scored 20 of his 26 points
in the first half and the Los Angeles Clippers beat the Houston Rockets 93-86 Monday night.
article.headline: Olowokandi, Brand help Clippers edge Rockets
article.linkText: Olowokandi helps Clippers snap two-game skid
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Michael Olowokandi scored 20 of his 26 points in the first half, then wondered where his teammates went. Olowokandi took just three shots in the second half when the Clippers stopped finding their center, but Los Angeles went on to beat the Houston Rockets 93-86 Monday night. "We definitely have to get better at feeding the post," Olowokandi said. "Half the time, we just dribble the ball and wind up passing the ball at the last minute and we throw the ball at bad angles. That's something the coach has to get on the guards about." Olowokandi picked up his fourth foul with 10:20 remaining in the game, then left the game for good with 1:16 to go and the Clippers clinging to a four-point lead. "I wasn't really upset," he said, explaining that coach Alvin Gentry kept telling him to go into the game, then go out. "I'm like, 'Make up your mind.' It's just one of those things where I think everyone was a little bit tense trying to get that win." The Clippers snapped a two-game losing skid and gained a half-game on Utah for the eighth and final Western Conference playoff spot. The Clippers are two behind the Jazz, with their next two games against Golden State and Phoenix -- both non-playoff teams. "We have to really hone down and win if we want to catch Utah," said Elton Brand, who had 20 points and 12 rebounds for the Clippers, who have won eight of their last 11 and are trying to make the playoffs for the first time since 1997. Gentry lamented Olowokandi's lack of shots in the second half. The Clippers were able to hold the Rockets to less than 30 points in all but the third quarter. "When Michael's going that well, we've got to find a way to get him the ball more. We just can't have a guy that's on a roll like that get three shots in the second half," Gentry said. "If they're playing him that well, then we've got to make sure somebody else is open or we're getting layups." Los Angeles set a franchise record by holding its 11th consecutive opponent under 100 points. The old mark of 10 in a row was set last November. "They came hard and did a good job on us. The defensive schemes that they put on were difficult," said Cuttino Mobley, who had 21 points for Houston. Steve Francis led Houston with 23 points and nine assists in his first game back after sitting out Saturday's double-overtime loss to Chicago because of recurring migraine headaches. Olowokandi, who grabbed 11 rebounds, got his fifth foul with 2:50 remaining and the Clippers ahead 84-79. Mobley scored four points in a row to draw the Rockets to 85-83. The Clippers' Darius Miles made one of two free throws for an 86-83 lead before Walt Williams missed a 3-pointer and Kelvin Cato received a technical for arguing with an official. Jeff McInnis, who had 10 of his 15 points in the fourth quarter, hit the free throw to keep Los Angeles ahead 87-83 with 1:40 remaining. Williams lost the ball out of bounds and Doug Overton, recently signed to a second 10-day contract, hit a running jumper to give the Clippers an 89-83 lead with 25 seconds left. Mobley hit a 3-pointer with 22 seconds left that drew Houston within three before McInnis got fouled and made two free throws for a 91-86 lead. Mobley missed a 3-pointer and the Rockets were forced to foul over the final 15 seconds. "They made the defensive plays down the stretch and we didn't. They cover a lot of ground and they're very active out there," Williams said. The Clippers led by 11 points early in the third quarter, then the Rockets outscored them 26-8. Houston took its first lead of the game on a dunk by Cato during the spurt that put the Rockets ahead 63-58 with 3:45 remaining. They shot a sizzling 70 percent in the quarter. Los Angeles got back into it on an 11-4 run to end the half ahead 69-67. Olowokandi scored four points -- his first of the second half. Game notes
Houston starting forward Kenny Thomas didn't return for the second half after straining his left quad. Teammate Eddie Griffin left with 2:49 remaining in the second quarter because of a sprained ankle. ... The crowd of 19,208 was the Clippers' ninth consecutive sellout and 18th of the season. ... Los Angeles improved to 3-1 against Houston this season. ... The Clippers now have 23 home victories, one more than last season.
